                <div class="work-description">
                    <h2>About The Piece</h2>
                    <p>“Drilled Into Memory” was created as part of a drawing assignment exploring unconventional points of view. Instead of a dramatic angle or an abstract scene, this piece pulls the viewer into a deeply personal moment—seen from a perspective no one else could ever witness: the back of the throat.</p>
                    <p>The drawing recreates a childhood memory that has lingered like a scar. I was under nitrous oxide, semi-conscious, surrounded by masked dentists, machines, and the sharp tools of their trade. In that moment, I felt helpless—awake inside my body, but unable to speak. That experience, both clinical and surreal, inspired the eerie viewpoint and the almost cartoonlike exaggeration of the hovering figures.</p>
                    <p>The teeth form a natural frame, while the two dentists loom large, frozen in a moment of intrusion. It’s a piece about medical memory, vulnerability, and the quiet trauma that gets etched into the body like it does on paper.</p>
                    <p>“Drilled Into Memory” turns an ordinary dental visit into an uncanny scene, transforming fear into visual narrative.</p>
